        </div>
        <div class="col-md-6 order-md-1">
            <h4>Unwanted behavior: train your kitten!</h4>
            <p>
                Cats, especially younger ones, are prone to engage in play that involves scratching or biting at people's hands while playing
                with them or random objects and furniture; this can lead to worse destructive behaviors without correction. Kittens are just
                trying to practice the skills they would usually need for survival, and it's best to redirect this behavior to acceptable play
                objects like feather toys to help keep them active and enriched without damaging you or your environment. Discouraging bad
                behavior should never involve hitting or flicking your cat because it can be interpreted as play, which is why redirection as
                enoucragement can be so important. Many cats are food-driven and treats are a wonderful encouragement tool as well!
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
